  "method": [
    {
      "heading": null,
      "description": "Combine all of your dry rub ingredients and mix well. This will make more than you need, store the excess in an airtight container in your spice cupboard!"
    },
    {
      "heading": null,
      "description": "Place your pork onto a baking tray and sprinkle generously with 5-6 tbsp of the rub until covered on all sides. Leave to sit for an hour or so to allow the rub to adhere."
    },
    {
      "heading": null,
      "description": "Place a large, deep pot (ideally cast iron) with a lid into the oven. Whack your oven on full blast (250°C)."
    },
    {
      "heading": null,
      "description": "Once heated, remove the pot, pour in a splash of oil and add the pork shoulder. Return to the oven for 10 mins to form a bark"
    },
    {
      "heading": null,
      "description": "Take the pork out of the oven again, pour the beer around it, cover with a lid and return to the oven. Turn down to 150°C and leave for 4 hours."
    },
    {
      "heading": null,
      "description": "While your pork is cooking you can knock up a quick slaw. Use a peeler to get long ribbons of carrot. Thinly slice your cabbage and onion. Combine in a colander and add sugar, salt and vinegar. Leave over a bowl to drain."
    },
    {
      "heading": null,
      "description": "After an hour, transfer the veg to a large bowl and add the mayonnaise."
    },
    {
      "heading": null,
      "description": "When the pork has had four hours, remove it from the oven. Using two forks, pull the pork and give it a mix. Taste and season with more rub if necessary!"
    },
    {
      "heading": null,
      "description": "Toast your ciabatta, slice in half, pile in your pulled pork, top with some slaw and, if you like, your favourite condiment."
    }
  ],
